<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-793-936  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 793 936.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Oct 23 1989 n561 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical drives go mainstream: erasable business is 'really juststarting.'andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lammers, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several companies have announced product enhancements in theerasable optical disk drive market that might help to bring thesedrives into the mainstream.andP;  Some of these companies includeHitachi Ltd and Kokusai Denshin Denwa Corp (KDD Corp), which areworking together to overcome the double-pass problem, wherein adrive head must make one pass to erase a sector before rewritingon the second pass.andP;  Mitsubishi Electric Corp has announced anerasable drive that reduces the average seek time by more than 40percent.andP;  Pioneer Electric Corp is working with KDD on arewritable optical disk system for the analog recording of colorimages.andP;  While optical drives lag in speed and price performance,they offer removable cartridges that hold from 327 to 640Mbytes ofdata per side.andP;  One analyst estimates that the business will juststart in 1990 in terms of production-use drives.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hitachi Ltd. (product development)Kokusai Denshin Denwa Company Ltd. (product development)Mitsubishi Electric Corp. (product development)Pioneer Electronic Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    HIT.andO;Topic:     Optical DisksErasable Optical MemoryMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesStorage Capacity.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Optical drives eye a place in the storage world. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>